<DOC><DOCNO> AP880601-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2010EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-AIDSHotLine     06-01 0216</FIRST><SECOND>AM-AIDS Hot Line,0220</SECOND><HEAD>Hot Line Expands As Calls Accelerate</HEAD><DATELINE>RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An AIDS hot line hasexpanded from 130 operators to 220 to accommodate a rush of callsgenerated in part by an educational pamphlet mailed to 10 millionU.S. homes, officials said.   ``We're still in the beginning of the rush,'' said CarolHumphries, coordinator for the National AIDS Hotline in ResearchTriangle Park. ``Not everybody in the country has gotten thepamphlet yet.''   The government pamphlet ``Understanding AIDS'' forced hot lineofficials to recruit operators through advertisements, flyers andthe news media.   The 24-hour hot line, 1-800-342-AIDS, offers referrals inEnglish and Spanish for people seeking help in their areas foracquired immune deficiency syndrome. Officials expect 2 millioncalls in 1988.   ``I think we're going to be at full capacity once we geteveryone trained,'' Ms. Humphries said. ``Things have been goingrather smoothly.''   The hot line is run by the American Social Health Associationunder contract with the U.S. Centers for Disease Control.   AIDS attacks the body's immune system, leaving it defenseless tomany diseases. It is spread most often through sexual contact,needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or bloodproducts, and from pregnant women to their offspring. There is noknown cure.</TEXT></DOC>